## Implied Captial Charge, accounting for exposure
- Doug’s example applies a binary (zero–one) weighting scheme, where a region’s peril AAL is set to zero if that peril is not covered in the region. 
- In practice, however, regions rarely have truly zero exposure to a given peril.
To address this, I suggest using exposure-based weighting.

Given a region $r$, for each peril, define an exposure-adjusted AAL:

$$
\mathrm{EAAL}(p,r) = \frac{
    \bigl(
        \sum_p \mathrm{AAL}(p,r)
        \bigr) \mathrm{EXP}(p,r)
}{
    \sum_p \mathrm{EXP}(p,r) \mathrm{AAL}(p,r)
} \mathrm{AAL}(p,r).
$$
This formulation emphasizes perils with greater exposure while preserving the total AAL at the regional level. Specifically,

$$
\sum_p
\mathrm{EAAL}(p,r) = \frac{
    \bigl(
        \sum_p \mathrm{AAL}(p,r)
        \bigr) 
        \sum_p
        \mathrm{EXP}(p,r) \mathrm{AAL}(p,r)
}{
    \sum_p \mathrm{EXP}(p,r) \mathrm{AAL}(p,r)
} = 
 \sum_p \mathrm{AAL}(p,r)
$$
and do all calculation of ICC and WPLR with EAAL rather than AAL.